\f0\fs28 \cf0 As well as being able to split the editor to view more than one document, you can open documents in their own windows, allowing you to have as many documents in a project open on screen as you want. We call these windows \'93Quick Reference\'94 panels, because you can use them to open, check and edit documents without affecting the main window.
\b\fs36 \cf2 \

\b0\fs28 \cf0 Let\'92s start by opening this document in a Quick Reference panel so that we can keep it open while we open some others:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Click the \'93Quick Ref\'94 icon in the toolbar (the one with the yellow pencil in it).\
{\listtext	2.	}Resize the window that appears as you wish, so that you can still see the main window behind it.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 You should now be reading this document inside the Quick Reference panel. You can change the label and status associated with a document using the pop-up buttons in the footer bar of the Quick Reference panel. You can also view the synopsis, notes and other metadata associated with the document using the pop-up button in the top-right of the window.\
